In those days a patron was more important than he would be at present, for then there were no copyright laws, and authors received little, if anything, from the sale of their works. Hence, one who devoted himself wholly to lit- erary pursuits was bound to rely on some patron for support, 'unless he possessed an independent fortune. Another patron of letters was Marcus Valerius Messala, a member of an illus· trious patrician family. Chief among those who gathered about him were Tibullus and Ovid.
